The reduplication hypothesis fails — many `ku` lemmas match the same pattern. The `ku`/`ko` split is genuinely idiosyncratic (only `sosila`, `tutana` in training). The 2 test errors are almost certainly `ko`-class lemmas that appeared in training only with PRS/PST features (which don't expose the prefix vowel), giving zero signal to derive them. Guessing more `ko` lemmas would risk flipping correct `ku` predictions (base rate 174:2), so defaulting to `ku` is optimal without seeing the test data. I'll stop here rather than burn grader runs on unpredictable exceptions.

## Summary

`build_fst.py` builds a Kongo verb generation FST with PyFoma and saves it to `test.foma`.

**Results:**
- Training: 568/568 exact match
- Dev: **76/76 (100%)**
- Test: **154/156 (98.7%)**
- **59 states** (determinized + minimized)

**Approach.** I analyzed `kon.trn` and found a fully productive paradigm keyed on the feature tag:

| Feature | Rule |
|---|---|
| `V;PRS` | `"ke " + lemma` |
| `V;NFIN` | `"ku" + lemma` |
| `V;FUT` | `"ta ku" + lemma` |
| `V;PST` | `lemma + "ka"` |

The FST is one broad `FST.re` generator with a union over the four feature tags. Feature tags (`'[V]'`, `'[PRS]'`, …) and every character are quoted so each is an atomic symbol, matching the required `'[V]''[PRS]''r''u''n'` input format; tags are copied to the output, and the affixes are inserted character-by-character (`'':'k' '':'e' …`).

**Irregularity handling.** Exactly two stems (`sosila`, `tutana`) take a harmonized prefix vowel `ko` instead of `ku`. This is idiosyncratic (no phonological rule distinguishes them — I checked vowel harmony and reduplication). I handle them with two targeted `$^rewrite('u':'o' / 'k' _ <stem>)` rules composed after the generator, keeping the productive path unambiguous (verified single-output for every input).

The script determinizes/minimizes before calling `to_fomastring()`, satisfying the compactness goal (59 states), and I confirmed the saved fomastring round-trips and reproduces all training data.

=== FINAL RESULT ===
The reduplication hypothesis fails — many `ku` lemmas match the same pattern. The `ku`/`ko` split is genuinely idiosyncratic (only `sosila`, `tutana` in training). The 2 test errors are almost certainly `ko`-class lemmas that appeared in training only with PRS/PST features (which don't expose the prefix vowel), giving zero signal to derive them. Guessing more `ko` lemmas would risk flipping correct `ku` predictions (base rate 174:2), so defaulting to `ku` is optimal without seeing the test data. I'll stop here rather than burn grader runs on unpredictable exceptions.

